   "source": [
    "# For loops"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Learning Objectives"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "* Understand how `for` loops can allow us to perform the same operations on different data "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Introduction to the For Loop"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "A `for` loop in Python, is good at going through elements of a list one by one.  Let's take an initial array."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "zero_to_three = [0, 1, 2, 3]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now to print the elements of a list, we could do the following: "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "0\n",
      "1\n",
      "2\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "print(zero_to_three[0])\n",
    "print(zero_to_three[1])\n",
    "print(zero_to_three[2])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "> Press shift + enter"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "So in the code above, we increased the index by one each time, going from the 0 to 1 to 2.  A `for` loop is great at going through sequential elements in a list, like 0 through 2.  For example:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "5\n",
      "6\n",
      "7\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "for i in [0, 1, 2]:\n",
    "    print(i + 5)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "> Again, press shift + enter"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "So above, our expression prints three times -- once for each element in our list.  The first time it starts with the number 0, as that is the first element in the array.  Then it goes forward to the second element\n",
    "and then the third.  So we can use the `for` loop to operate on the numbers zero through two, and the `i` represents a successive element in our list each time.\n",
    "\n",
    "Pay careful attention to the syntax.  What is that colon at the end of the first line?  Essentially, Python needs to know when the body of the loop begins and when it ends.  So we mark the beginning of the loop's body with a colon, `:`, and then indent each successive line of the loop.  (If you press enter after the colon, the next line will automatically indent).  To end the body of the loop, we simply unindent. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "5\n",
      "6\n",
      "7\n",
      "10\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "for i in [0, 1, 2]:\n",
    "    print(i + 5)\n",
    "print(10)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Just like any other variable, we can call the `i` whatever we like.  Below, we call it `number`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {
    "scrolled": true
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "5\n",
      "6\n",
      "7\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "for number in [0, 1, 2]:\n",
    "    print(number + 5)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Whichever word we place after the `for` keyword will be the name of our loop variable to reference later on.  If we are inconsistent, we receive an error."
   ]
  }